    body:
      'Iter 144. Direct follow-on to iter 143\'s queued candidate (b) — per-endpoint timeout override map. iter 143 landed the AbortController fail-fast that converted the 2026-06-15 Taostats outage from 60s Vercel kill + 504-no-body into 15s 500-JSON-with-fallback, but the 15s blanket was suboptimal in both directions for normal operation. Lightweight single-record endpoints (/api/price/latest/v1, /api/account/latest/v1) respond in <1s on a healthy Pro plan — when they hang, the 15s wait adds ~14s of useless dead time to the report build, eating budget that could be left for the rest of the parallel fanout. Heavy server-aggregating endpoints (/api/accounting/tax/v1 returns a full FY of tax events with server-side classification, /api/account/history/v1 with limit=200 page=N on a high-activity wallet, /api/delegation/v1 same shape) can legitimately take 8–12s on cold cache and would false-positive timeout under the 15s blanket on a wallet that just needs a few more seconds. iter 144 ships TAOSTATS_PATH_TIMEOUTS, an exact-path-match override map: /api/price/latest/v1 → 5s, /api/account/latest/v1 → 8s, /api/dtao/validator/yield/latest/v1 → 12s, /api/account/history/v1 → 20s, /api/transfer/v1 → 20s, /api/delegation/v1 → 20s, /api/dtao/coldkey_alpha_shares/latest/v1 → 18s, /api/accounting/tax/v1 → 25s. timeoutFor(path) returns the override or falls back to iter 143\'s TAOSTATS_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_MS (15s, still env-configurable via TAOSTATS_TIMEOUT_MS for emergency tuning of unmapped paths). taoGet captures timeoutMs once at the top of each call and uses that for both the AbortController setTimeout and the error message text — so an aborted /api/price/latest/v1 throws "Taostats /api/price/latest/v1 → timeout after 5000ms" rather than the misleading "after 15000ms" the iter 143 message would have produced. Per-endpoint env overrides intentionally NOT added — keeps the map auditable in one place rather than scattered across N env vars, and there\'s no current operational use-case for per-path env tuning on prod that emergency editing of the map + redeploy wouldn\'t cover faster. Pre-commit smoke 13/13 PASS on isolated cases: all 8 mapped paths return their override values exactly, 3 unmapped paths (/api/unknown/endpoint/v1, /api/foo/bar, empty string) fall through to default 15000ms, ordering invariant holds (light 5s < med 12s < default 15s < heavy 25s), all map values are positive finite ≤30s. Non-regressive: AbortError fail-fast (no retry on timeout), 429/5xx retry logic, transport-error retry, the auth headers path, and every consumer of taoGet — all unchanged. Strict improvement on iter 143: same safety floor against multi-hour outages (unmapped paths still get 15s), better failure latency on light endpoints (5–8s instead of 15s, 47–67% faster), better headroom on heavy endpoints (20–25s instead of 15s, 33–67% more) for healthy-but-loaded Taostats Pro days. KB layer-stack unchanged (FIFTEEN — reliability infra, not a verdict axis). KB→§0 bridges unchanged (EIGHT). Taostats outage continues at iter 144 fire (00:00Z, 3h+ now) — retroactive iter 142 verify still blocked but the upstream-block detection signal from this iter\'s 5s price/latest timeout would let a future "Taostats degraded" banner (iter 145 candidate c) fire 3x faster on outage-onset. Iter 145 candidates: (a) retroactive iter 142 live verify on Jai\'s 7 pinned coldkeys (still queued from iter 142 — once Taostats recovers), (b) "Taostats degraded" §0 banner that fires when one or more sections returned a timeout (currently silently soft-omitted by the .catch wrappers — fine for graceful degradation but invisible to the user trying to diagnose why a section is missing — the per-endpoint timeouts from iter 144 give the banner finer-grained detection: a /api/price/latest/v1 timeout in 5s is a strong upstream signal vs. a /api/accounting/tax/v1 timeout in 25s which could be just a heavy load read), (c) surface the parity verdict from iter 142 as a chip in the §2 PnL UI block (UI-only, no API dependency — could ship in parallel with Taostats outage), (d) per-section timeout budget tracking in the report response so the user can see "tax fetch took 24.8s / 25s budget" or "price fetch failed at 5.0s / 5s budget" in a diagnostic panel. PR #1 (iter 140 free-PnL preview branch) still OPEN, no Jai reply since 2026-05-28T07:55:09Z (~19 days, awaiting 1/2/3 signoff on the priority redirect itself, not specifically PR #1).',
